# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] An **aisle** is a linear space for walking with rows of non-walking spaces on both sides.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Aisles with seating on both sides can be seen in airplanes, in buildings such as churches, cathedrals, synagogues, meeting halls, parliaments, courtrooms, theatres, and in long passenger vehicles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] An aisle floor may be level or, as in theatres, sloping upward from a stage.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Aisles also cross through shops, where they have shelving on either side; warehouses, flanked by storage pallets; and factories, where they separate different work areas.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In health clubs, exercise equipment is normally arranged along aisles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] They are distinguished from corridors, hallways, walkways, footpaths, pavements (*American English* sidewalks), trails, paths and open areas of buildings: aisles lie between other open or seating areas, which are all enclosed within a structure.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Spaces between buildings are not considered aisles, regardless of their size.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] The word is related to French *aile* (wing).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In architecture, an aisle is more specifically the wing of a house, or a lateral division of a large building.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] The earliest examples of aisles date back to the Roman times and can be found in the Basilica Ulpia (basilica of Trajan), which had double aisles on either side of its central area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In church architecture, an aisle (also known as an *yle* or *alley*) is more specifically a passageway to either side of the nave that is separated from the nave by colonnades or arcades, a row of pillars or columns.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Occasionally aisles stop at the transepts, but often aisles can be continued around the apse.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Aisles are thus categorized as *nave-aisles*, *transept-aisles* or *choir-aisles*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] A semi-circular choir with aisles continued around it, providing access to a series of chapels, is a chevet.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In Gothic architecture, the aisles' roofs are lower than that of the nave, allowing light to enter through clerestory windows.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In Romanesque architecture, however, the roofs are at roughly equal heights, with those of the aisle being only slightly lower than that of the nave.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In Germany, churches where the roofs of the aisles and nave are the same height, such as St.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Stephen's, Vienna, the Wiesenkirche at Soest, St.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Martin's, Landshut, and the Frauenkirche (Church of Our Lady) in Munich are known as *Hallenkirchen*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] When discussing overall design, architectural historians include the centrally-positioned nave in the number of aisles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Thus the original St Peter's Basilica in Rome, Milan Cathedral, Amiens Cathedral, Notre Dame de Paris and Alexander Nevsky Cathedral in Sofia are all described as having five aisles, meaning they have two side aisles either side of the nave.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Antwerp Cathedral even has seven aisles (three at either side of the central nave).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In the United Kingdom, cathedrals generally only have one aisle on each side, with Chichester Cathedral, Elgin Cathedral and St Mary Magdalene, Taunton being the only three exceptions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In supermarkets there are two types of aisles, food aisles and checkout aisles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In retail stores that do not primarily sell food, aisles containing products would be referred to either generically as **merchandise aisles**, or by the particular products contained in the aisle, e.g., "the gardening aisle", "the sports equipment aisle".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] For customer convenience, supermarkets and retail stores commonly number the aisles and have signs indicating both the aisle number and the types of products displayed in that aisle.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Churches, courtrooms, legislatures, and meeting halls may identify individual rows, seats or sections but do not normally assign aisle numbers or display signs regarding aisles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] The spaces between rows of book shelves in the "stacks" area are called aisles and desks in the reading area are frequently arranged in rows with aisles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Server rooms are typically divided into hot and cold aisles for cooling efficiency, and access to servers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Theatre-type seating in a lecture hall with a stair aisle.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Films, stage plays and musical concerts ordinarily are presented in a darkened facility so the audience can see the presentation better.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] To improve safety, often the edges of the aisles in such facilities are marked with a row of small lights.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] The markers frequently are strings of light-emitting diodes (LEDs) because LEDs are durable, have low power consumption and use low voltages that are not subject to electrical codes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] To provide a higher level of light focused downward, lighting fixtures referred to as luminaries are often built into the side of the seat facing the aisle.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Sport stadiums and outdoor arenas frequently have several types of aisles, including aisles to purchase tickets for events, aisles to enter the main event area and aisles to go to seating.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Stadium seating routinely is separated into sections by aisles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Seating rows are accessed by stairsteps.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] To promote safety, aisles commonly are divided by a handrail in the middle of the aisle.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] The floor plan of aisled barns resembles that of an aisled church.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] However, the nave in farm buildings is called an aisle thus a "three aisled barn".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Aisled barns have the big barn doors on the gable end of the building giving access to the center aisle, often called the drive floor or threshing floor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] The side aisles may be the same widths making the barn symmetrical or the aisle where animals were housed may be narrower which is apparent outside the barn because the barn doors are then off-center.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] The area between the posts, perpendicular to the aisles are called bays.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] In stables there is a **stable aisle** down the centre with individual stalls facing the aisle.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] On vehicles, the aisle is more specifically a passageway for passengers to move along within the vehicle.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] National and local government regulations require a minimum width for aisles in various building types.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Regulatory agencies frequently inspect buildings, vehicles, etc., to enforce regulations requiring that aisles not be restricted.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Inspectors have imposed fines for blocking or restricting passage when boxes or folding chairs are stored in aisles, for example.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Insurance companies frequently have safety inspectors to examine the premises, both to determine whether insureds are complying with the insurer's requirements for coverage and to look for any practices that could lead to injury or property damage, including restricting passage in aisles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] The Americans with Disabilities Act sets certain standards for building access and other design considerations in all new construction and major renovations in the U.S.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] An **architectural barrier** is any feature that makes access or use of a building difficult, unreasonably dangerous or impossible.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] This can include aisles that are too narrow for easy access by a wheelchair.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Often, the only way to get from a row of chairs, shelves, workstations, etc., to an exit is by an aisle.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Historically, many deaths and serious injuries have occurred due to fire, inhalation of smoke or noxious fumes, etc., because blocked or partially blocked aisles prevented persons from promptly leaving a dangerous area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Regulations applicable to public carriers transporting passengers often require aisles to be completely clear in vehicles, such as airlines, buses and trains.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/aisle] Many insurance companies have requirements regarding minimum aisle width, unrestricted aisles and easy access to exits, and will refuse to insure companies that do not meet their requirements or will increase the premiums on companies that frequently violate the requirements.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In modern historiography, **ancient Rome** is the Roman civilisation from the founding of the Italian city of Rome in the 8th century BC to the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] It encompasses the Roman Kingdom (753–509 BC), the Roman Republic (509‍–‍27 BC), and the Roman Empire (27 BC – 476 AD) until the fall of the western empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome began as an Italic settlement, traditionally dated to 753 BC, beside the River Tiber in the Italian Peninsula.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The settlement grew into the city and polity of Rome, and came to control its neighbours through a combination of treaties and military strength.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] It eventually controlled the Italian Peninsula, assimilating the Greek culture of southern Italy (Magna Graecia) and the Etruscan culture, and then became the dominant power in the Mediterranean region and parts of Europe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] At its height it controlled the North African coast, Egypt, Southern Europe, and most of Western Europe, the Balkans, Crimea, and much of the Middle East, including Anatolia, the Levant, and parts of Mesopotamia and Arabia.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] That empire was among the largest empires in the ancient world, covering around 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles) in AD 117, with an estimated 50 to 90 million inhabitants, roughly 20% of the world's population at the time.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman state evolved from an elective monarchy to a classical republic and then to an increasingly autocratic military dictatorship during the Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome is often grouped into classical antiquity together with ancient Greece, and their similar cultures and societies are known as the Greco-Roman world.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Roman civilisation has contributed to modern language, religion, society, technology, law, politics, government, warfare, art, literature, architecture, and engineering.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Rome professionalised and expanded its military and created a system of government called *res publica*, the inspiration for modern republics such as the United States and France.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] It achieved impressive technological and architectural feats, such as the empire-wide construction of aqueducts and roads, as well as more grandiose monuments and facilities.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence of settlement around Rome starts to emerge c.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Large-scale organisation appears only c.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] 800 BC, with the first graves in the Esquiline Hill's necropolis, along with a clay and timber wall on the bottom of the Palatine Hill dating to the middle of the 8th century BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] 650 BC, the Romans started to drain the valley between the Capitoline and Palatine Hills, where today sits the Roman Forum.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] By the 6th century BC, the Romans were constructing the Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus on the Capitoline and expanding to the Forum Boarium located between the Capitoline and Aventine Hills.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans themselves had a founding myth, attributing their city to Romulus and Remus, offspring of Mars and a princess of the mythical city of Alba Longa.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The sons, sentenced to death, were rescued by a wolf and returned to restore the Alban king and found a city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After a dispute, Romulus killed Remus and became the city's sole founder.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The area of his initial settlement on the Palatine Hill was later known as Roma quadrata ('Square Rome').
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The story dates at least to the 3rd century BC, and the later Roman antiquarian Marcus Terentius Varro placed the city's foundation to 753 BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Another legend, recorded by Greek historian Dionysius of Halicarnassus, says that Prince Aeneas led a group of Trojans on a sea voyage to found a new Troy after the Trojan War.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] They landed on the banks of the Tiber River and a woman travelling with them, Roma, torched their ships to prevent them from leaving again.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman poet Virgil recounted this legend in his classical epic poem the *Aeneid*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Literary and archaeological evidence is clear on there having been kings in Rome, attested in fragmentary 6th-century BC texts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Long after the abolition of the Roman monarchy, a vestigial *rex sacrorum* was retained to exercise the monarch's former priestly functions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans believed that their monarchy was elective, with seven legendary kings who were largely unrelated by blood.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Evidence of Roman expansion is clear in the 6th century BC; by its end, Rome controlled a territory of some 780 square kilometres (300 square miles) with a population perhaps as high as 35,000.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] 625 BC; the Romans attributed the creation of their first popular organisations and the Senate to the regal period as well.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Rome also started to extend its control over its Latin neighbours.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] While later Roman stories like the *Aeneid* asserted that all Latins descended from the character Aeneas, a common culture is attested to archaeologically.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Attested to reciprocal rights of marriage and citizenship between Latin cities—the *Jus Latii*—along with shared religious festivals, further indicate a shared culture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century, most of this area had become dominated by the Romans.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century BC, Rome and many of its Italian neighbours entered a period of turbulence.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence implies some degree of large-scale warfare.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] According to tradition and later writers such as Livy, the Roman Republic was established c.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] 509 BC, when the last of the seven kings of Rome, Tarquin the Proud, was deposed and a system based on annually elected magistrates and various representative assemblies was established.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] A constitution set a series of checks and balances, and a separation of powers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The most important magistrates were the two consuls, who together exercised executive authority such as *imperium*, or military command.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The consuls had to work with the Senate, which was initially an advisory council of the ranking nobility, or patricians, but grew in size and power.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Other magistrates of the Republic include tribunes, quaestors, aediles, praetors and censors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The magistracies were originally restricted to patricians, but were later opened to common people, or plebeians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Republican voting assemblies included the *comitia centuriata* ('centuriate assembly'), which voted on matters of war and peace and elected men to the most important offices, and the *comitia tributa* ('tribal assembly'), which elected less important offices.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the 4th century BC, Rome had come under attack by the Gauls, who now extended their power in the Italian peninsula beyond the Po Valley and through Etruria.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] On 16 July 390 BC, a Gallic army under the leadership of tribal chieftain Brennus, defeated the Romans at the Battle of the Allia and marched to Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls looted and burned the city, then laid siege to the Capitoline Hill, where some Romans had barricaded themselves, for seven months.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls then agreed to give the Romans peace in exchange for 1000 pounds of gold.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] According to later legend, the Roman supervising the weighing noticed that the Gauls were using false scales.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans then took up arms and defeated the Gauls.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans gradually subdued the other peoples on the Italian peninsula, including the Etruscans.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The last threat to Roman hegemony in Italy came when Tarentum, a major Greek colony, enlisted the aid of Pyrrhus of Epirus in 281 BC, but this effort failed as well.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans secured their conquests by founding Roman colonies in strategic areas, thereby establishing stable control over the region.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the 3rd century BC Rome faced a new and formidable opponent: Carthage, the other major power in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The First Punic War began in 264 BC, when the city of Messana asked for Carthage's help in their conflicts with Hiero II of Syracuse.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After the Carthaginian intercession, Messana asked Rome to expel the Carthaginians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Rome entered this war because Syracuse and Messana were too close to the newly conquered Greek cities of Southern Italy and Carthage was now able to make an offensive through Roman territory; along with this, Rome could extend its domain over Sicily.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage was a maritime power, and the Roman lack of ships and naval experience made the path to the victory a long and difficult one for the Roman Republic.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Despite this, after more than 20 years of war, Rome defeated Carthage and a peace treaty was signed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Among the reasons for the Second Punic War was the subsequent war reparations Carthage acquiesced to at the end of the First Punic War.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The war began with the audacious invasion of Hispania by Hannibal, who marched through Hispania to the Italian Alps.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Hannibal's invasion lasted over 16 years, ravaging Italy, but ultimately Carthage was defeated in the decisive Battle of Zama in October 202 BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] More than a half century after these events, Carthage was left humiliated and the Republic's focus was now directed towards the Hellenistic kingdoms of Greece and revolts in Hispania.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] However, Carthage, having paid the war indemnity, felt that its commitments and submission to Rome had ceased, a vision not shared by the Roman Senate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Third Punic War began when Rome declared war against Carthage in 149 BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage resisted well at the first strike but could not withstand the attack of Scipio Aemilianus, who entirely destroyed the city, enslaved all the citizens and gained control of that region, which became the province of Africa.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] All these wars resulted in Rome's first overseas conquests (Sicily, Hispania and Africa) and the rise of Rome as a significant imperial power.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating the Macedonian and Seleucid Empires in the 2nd century BC, the Romans became the dominant people of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms brought the Roman and Greek cultures in closer contact and the Roman elite, once rural, became cosmopolitan.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Foreign dominance led to internal strife.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Senators became rich at the provinces' expense; soldiers, who were mostly small-scale farmers, were away from home longer and could not maintain their land; and the increased reliance on foreign slaves and the growth of *latifundia* reduced the availability of paid work.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Income from war booty, mercantilism in the new provinces, and tax farming created new economic opportunities for the wealthy, forming a new class of merchants, called the equestrians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The **lex Claudia** forbade members of the Senate from engaging in commerce, so while the equestrians could theoretically join the Senate, they were severely restricted in political power.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate squabbled perpetually, repeatedly blocked important land reforms and refused to give the equestrian class a larger say in the government.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Violent gangs of the urban unemployed, controlled by rival Senators, intimidated the electorate through violence.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The situation came to a head in the late 2nd century BC under the Gracchi brothers, a pair of tribunes who attempted to pass land reform legislation that would redistribute the major patrician landholdings among the plebeians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Both brothers were killed and the Senate passed reforms reversing the Gracchi brother's actions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] This led to the growing divide of the plebeian groups (*populares*) and equestrian classes (*optimates*).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Gaius Marius soon became a leader of the Republic, holding the first of his seven consulships (an unprecedented number) in 107 BC by arguing that his former patron Quintus Caecilius Metellus Numidicus was not able to defeat and capture the Numidian king Jugurtha.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Marius then started his military reform: in his recruitment to fight Jugurtha, he levied the very poor (an innovation), and many landless men entered the army.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Marius was elected for five consecutive consulships from 104 to 100 BC, as Rome needed a military leader to defeat the Cimbri and the Teutones, who were threatening Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After Marius's retirement, Rome had a brief peace, during which the Italian *socii* ('allies') requested Roman citizenship and voting rights.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The reformist Marcus Livius Drusus supported their legal process but was assassinated, and the *socii* revolted against the Romans in the Social War.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] At one point both consuls were killed; Marius was appointed to command the army together with Lucius Julius Caesar and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Social War, Marius and Sulla were the premier military men in Rome and their partisans were in conflict, both sides jostling for power.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 88 BC, Sulla was elected for his first consulship and his first assignment was to defeat Mithridates VI of Pontus, whose intentions were to conquer the Eastern part of the Roman territories.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] However, Marius's partisans managed his installation to the military command, defying Sulla and the Senate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] To consolidate his own power, Sulla conducted a surprising and illegal action: he marched to Rome with his legions, killing all those who showed support to Marius's cause.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the following year, 87 BC, Marius, who had fled at Sulla's march, returned to Rome while Sulla was campaigning in Greece.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He seized power along with the consul Lucius Cornelius Cinna and killed the other consul, Gnaeus Octavius, achieving his seventh consulship.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Marius and Cinna revenged their partisans by conducting a massacre.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Marius died in 86 BC, due to age and poor health, just a few months after seizing power.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Cinna exercised absolute power until his death in 84 BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After returning from his Eastern campaigns, Sulla had a free path to reestablish his own power.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 83 BC he made his second march on Rome and began a time of terror: thousands of nobles, knights and senators were executed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla held two dictatorships and one more consulship, which began the crisis and decline of Roman Republic.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the mid-1st century BC, Roman politics were restless.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Political divisions in Rome split into one of two groups, *populares* (who hoped for the support of the people) and *optimates* (the 'best', who wanted to maintain exclusive aristocratic control).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla overthrew all populist leaders and his constitutional reforms removed powers (such as those of the tribune of the plebs) that had supported populist approaches.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Meanwhile, social and economic stresses continued to build; Rome had become a metropolis with a super-rich aristocracy, debt-ridden aspirants, and a large proletariat often of impoverished farmers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The latter groups supported the Catilinarian conspiracy—a resounding failure since the consul Marcus Tullius Cicero quickly arrested and executed the main leaders.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Julius Caesar reconciled the two most powerful men in Rome: Marcus Licinius Crassus, who had financed much of his earlier career, and Crassus' rival, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (anglicised as Pompey), to whom he married his daughter.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He formed them into a new informal alliance including himself, the First Triumvirate ('three men').
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's daughter died in childbirth in 54 BC, and in 53 BC, Crassus invaded Parthia and was killed in the Battle of Carrhae; the Triumvirate disintegrated.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar conquered Gaul, obtained immense wealth, respect in Rome and the loyalty of battle-hardened legions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He became a threat to Pompey and was loathed by many *optimates*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Confident that Caesar could be stopped by legal means, Pompey's party tried to strip Caesar of his legions, a prelude to Caesar's trial, impoverishment, and exile.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] To avoid this fate, Caesar crossed the Rubicon River and invaded Rome in 49 BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Battle of Pharsalus was a brilliant victory for Caesar and in this and other campaigns, he destroyed all of the *optimates* leaders: Metellus Scipio, Cato the Younger, and Pompey's son, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar was now pre-eminent over Rome: in five years he held four consulships, two ordinary dictatorships, and two special dictatorships, one for perpetuity.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered in 44 BC, on the Ides of March by the *Liberatores*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's assassination caused political and social turmoil in Rome; the city was ruled by his friend and colleague, Mark Antony.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Soon afterward, Octavian, whom Caesar adopted through his will, arrived in Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian (historians regard Octavius as Octavian due to the Roman naming conventions) tried to align himself with the Caesarian faction.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 43 BC, along with Antony and Marcus Aemilius Lepidus, Caesar's best friend, he legally established the Second Triumvirate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Upon its formation, 130–300 senators were executed, and their property was confiscated, due to their supposed support for the *Liberatores*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 42 BC, the Senate deified Caesar as *Divus Iulius*; Octavian thus became *Divi filius*, the son of the deified.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the same year, Octavian and Antony defeated both Caesar's assassins and the leaders of the *Liberatores*, Marcus Junius Brutus and Gaius Cassius Longinus, in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate was marked by the proscriptions of many senators and *equites*: after a revolt led by Antony's brother Lucius Antonius, more than 300 senators and *equites* involved were executed, although Lucius was spared.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Triumvirate divided the Empire among the triumvirs: Lepidus was given charge of Africa, Antony, the eastern provinces, and Octavian remained in Italia and controlled Hispania and Gaul.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate expired in 38 BC but was renewed for five more years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] However, the relationship between Octavian and Antony had deteriorated, and Lepidus was forced to retire in 36 BC after betraying Octavian in Sicily.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Triumvirate, Antony was living in Ptolemaic Egypt, ruled by his lover, Cleopatra VII.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Antony's affair with Cleopatra was seen as an act of treason, since she was queen of another country.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Additionally, Antony adopted a lifestyle considered too extravagant and Hellenistic for a Roman statesman.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Following Antony's Donations of Alexandria, which gave to Cleopatra the title of "Queen of Kings", and to Antony's and Cleopatra's children the regal titles to the newly conquered Eastern territories, war between Octavian and Antony broke out.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian annihilated Egyptian forces in the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Now Egypt was conquered by the Roman Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 27 BC and at the age of 36, Octavian was the sole Roman leader.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In that year, he took the name *Augustus*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] That event is usually taken by historians as the beginning of Roman Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Officially, the government was republican, but Augustus assumed absolute powers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His reform of the government brought about a two-century period colloquially referred to by Romans as the Pax Romana.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudian dynasty was established by Augustus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The emperors of this dynasty were Augustus, Tiberius, Caligula, Claudius and Nero.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians started the destruction of republican values, but on the other hand, they boosted Rome's status as the central power in the Mediterranean region.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] While Caligula and Nero are usually remembered in popular culture as dysfunctional emperors, Augustus and Claudius are remembered as successful in politics and the military.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] This dynasty instituted imperial tradition in Rome and frustrated any attempt to reestablish a Republic.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] 27 BC – AD 14) gathered almost all the republican powers under his official title, *princeps*, and diminished the political influence of the senatorial class by boosting the equestrian class.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The senators lost their right to rule certain provinces, like Egypt, since the governor of that province was directly nominated by the emperor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The creation of the Praetorian Guard and his reforms in the military, creating a standing army with a fixed size of 28 legions, ensured his total control over the army.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Compared with the Second Triumvirate's epoch, Augustus' reign as *princeps* was very peaceful, which led the people and the nobles of Rome to support Augustus, increasing his strength in political affairs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His generals were responsible for the field command, gaining such commanders as Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa, Nero Claudius Drusus and Germanicus much respect from the populace and the legions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus intended to extend the Roman Empire to the whole known world, and in his reign, Rome conquered Cantabria, Aquitania, Raetia, Dalmatia, Illyricum and Pannonia.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Under Augustus' reign, Roman literature grew steadily in what is known as the Golden Age of Latin Literature.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Poets like Virgil, Horace, Ovid and Rufus developed a rich literature, and were close friends of Augustus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Along with Maecenas, he sponsored patriotic poems, such as Virgil's epic *Aeneid* and historiographical works like those of Livy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus continued the changes to the calendar promoted by Caesar, and the month of August is named after him.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus brought a peaceful and thriving era to Rome, known as *Pax Romana*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians continued to rule Rome after Augustus' death in 14 AD and remained in power until the death of Nero in 68 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Influenced by his wife, Livia Drusilla, Augustus appointed her son from another marriage, Tiberius, as his heir.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate agreed with the succession, and granted to Tiberius the same titles and honours once granted to Augustus: the title of *princeps* and *Pater patriae*, and the Civic Crown.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] However, Tiberius was not an enthusiast for political affairs: after agreement with the Senate, he retired to Capri in 26 AD, and left control of the city of Rome in the hands of the praetorian prefect Sejanus (until 31 AD) and Macro (from 31 to 37 AD).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The male line of the Julio-Claudians was limited to Tiberius' nephew Claudius, his grandson Tiberius Gemellus and his grand-nephew Caligula.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] As Gemellus was still a child, Caligula was chosen to rule the empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He was a popular leader in the first half of his reign, but became a crude and insane tyrant in his years controlling government.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Praetorian Guard murdered Caligula four years after the death of Tiberius, and, with belated support from the senators, proclaimed his uncle Claudius as the new emperor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was not as authoritarian as Tiberius and Caligula.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius conquered Lycia and Thrace; his most important deed was the beginning of the conquest of Britannia.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was poisoned by his wife, Agrippina the Younger in 54 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His heir was Nero, son of Agrippina and her former husband, since Claudius' son Britannicus had not reached manhood upon his father's death.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Nero sent his general, Suetonius Paulinus, to invade modern-day Wales, where he encountered stiff resistance.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Celts there were independent, tough, resistant to tax collectors, and fought Paulinus as he battled his way across from east to west.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] It took him a long time to reach the north-west coast, and in 60 AD he finally crossed the Menai Strait to the sacred island of Mona (Anglesey), the last stronghold of the druids.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His soldiers attacked the island and massacred the druids: men, women and children, destroyed the shrine and the sacred groves and threw many of the sacred standing stones into the sea.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] While Paulinus and his troops were massacring druids in Mona, the tribes of modern-day East Anglia staged a revolt led by queen Boadicea of the Iceni.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The rebels sacked and burned Camulodunum, Londinium and Verulamium (modern-day Colchester, London and St Albans respectively) before they were crushed by Paulinus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Boadicea, like Cleopatra before her, committed suicide to avoid the disgrace of being paraded in triumph in Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Nero is widely known as the first persecutor of Christians and for the Great Fire of Rome, rumoured to have been started by the emperor himself.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] A conspiracy against Nero in 65 AD under Calpurnius Piso failed, but in 68 AD the armies under Julius Vindex in Gaul and Servius Sulpicius Galba in modern-day Spain revolted.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Deserted by the Praetorian Guards and condemned to death by the senate, Nero killed himself.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Flavians were the second dynasty to rule Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] By 68 AD, the year of Nero's death, there was no chance of a return to the Republic, and so a new emperor had to arise.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After the turmoil in the Year of the Four Emperors, Titus Flavius Vespasianus (anglicised as Vespasian) took control of the empire and established a new dynasty.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Under the Flavians, Rome continued its expansion, and the state remained secure.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The most significant military campaign undertaken during the Flavian period was the siege and destruction of Jerusalem in 70 AD by Titus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The destruction of the city was the culmination of the Roman campaign in Judea following the Jewish uprising of 66 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Temple was completely demolished, after which Titus' soldiers proclaimed him *imperator* in honour of the victory.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Jerusalem was sacked and much of the population killed or dispersed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Josephus claims that 1,100,000 people were killed during the siege, of whom a majority were Jewish, and 97,000 were captured and enslaved.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Many fled to areas around the Mediterranean.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was a general under Claudius and Nero and fought as a commander in the First Jewish-Roman War.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Following the turmoil of the Year of the Four Emperors, in 69 AD, four emperors were enthroned in turn: Galba, Otho, Vitellius, and, lastly, Vespasian, who crushed Vitellius' forces and became emperor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He reconstructed many buildings which were uncompleted, like a statue of Apollo and the temple of *Divus Claudius* ("the deified Claudius"), both initiated by Nero.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Buildings destroyed by the Great Fire of Rome were rebuilt, and he revitalised the Capitol.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian started the construction of the Flavian Amphitheater, commonly known as the Colosseum.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The historians Josephus and Pliny the Elder wrote their works during Vespasian's reign.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was Josephus' sponsor and Pliny dedicated his *Naturalis Historia* to Titus, son of Vespasian.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian sent legions to defend the eastern frontier in Cappadocia, extended the occupation in Britannia (modern-day England, Wales and southern Scotland) and reformed the tax system.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He finished the Flavian Amphitheater, using war spoils from the First Jewish-Roman War, and hosted victory games that lasted for a hundred days.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] These games included gladiatorial combats, horse races and a sensational mock naval battle on the flooded grounds of the Colosseum.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Titus died of fever in 81 AD, and was succeeded by his brother Domitian.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] As emperor, Domitian showed the characteristics of a tyrant.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He ruled for fifteen years, during which time he acquired a reputation for self-promotion as a living god.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed at least two temples in honour of Jupiter, the supreme deity in Roman religion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered following a plot within his own household.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Following Domitian's murder, the Senate rapidly appointed Nerva as Emperor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva had noble ancestry, and he had served as an advisor to Nero and the Flavians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His rule restored many of the traditional liberties of Rome's upper classes, which Domitian had over-ridden.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva–Antonine dynasty from 96 AD to 192 AD included the "five good emperors" Nerva, Trajan, Hadrian, Antoninus Pius and Marcus Aurelius.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva-Antonine dynasty came to an end with Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva abdicated and died in 98 AD, and was succeeded by the general Trajan.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan is credited with the restoration of traditional privileges and rights of commoner and senatorial classes, which later Roman historians claim to have been eroded during Domitian's autocracy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan fought three Dacian wars, winning territories roughly equivalent to modern-day Romania and Moldova.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He undertook an ambitious public building program in Rome, including Trajan's Forum, Trajan's Market and Trajan's Column, with the architect Apollodorus of Damascus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He remodelled the Pantheon and extended the Circus Maximus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia appointed a king for Armenia without consulting Rome, Trajan declared war on Parthia and deposed the king of Armenia.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 115 he took the Northern Mesopotamian cities of Nisibis and Batnae, organised a province of Mesopotamia (116), and issued coins that claimed Armenia and Mesopotamia were under the authority of the Roman people.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year, he captured Seleucia and the Parthian capital Ctesiphon (near modern Baghdad).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating a Parthian revolt and a Jewish revolt, he withdrew due to health issues, and in 117, he died of edema.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Under Trajan, the Roman Empire had reached the peak of its territorial expansion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Rome's dominion now spanned 5.0 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan's successor Hadrian withdrew all the troops stationed in Parthia, Armenia and Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq), abandoning Trajan's conquests.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian's army crushed a revolt in Mauretania and the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] This was the last large-scale Jewish revolt against the Romans, and was suppressed with massive repercussions in Judea.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Jews were killed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian renamed the province of Judea "Provincia Syria Palaestina", after one of Judea's most hated enemies.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed fortifications and walls, like the celebrated Hadrian's Wall which separated Roman Britannia and the tribes of modern-day Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian promoted culture, especially the Greek.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He forbade torture and humanised the laws.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His many building projects included aqueducts, baths, libraries and theatres; additionally, he travelled nearly every province in the Empire to review military and infrastructural conditions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Following Hadrian's death in 138 AD, his successor Antoninus Pius built temples, theatres, and mausoleums, promoted the arts and sciences, and bestowed honours and financial rewards upon the teachers of rhetoric and philosophy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] On becoming emperor, Antoninus made few initial changes, leaving intact as far as possible the arrangements instituted by his predecessor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Antoninus expanded Roman Britannia by invading what is now southern Scotland and building the Antonine Wall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He also continued Hadrian's policy of humanising the laws.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His reign was the most peaceful in the entire history of Roman Empire, he left "an empire in very fine shape.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] It was a height that, arguably, it would never reach again." He died in 161 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Marcus Aurelius, known as the Philosopher, was the last of the Five Good Emperors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He was a stoic philosopher and wrote the *Meditations*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He defeated barbarian tribes in the Marcomannic Wars as well as the Parthian Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His co-emperor, Lucius Verus, died in 169 AD, probably from the Antonine Plague, a pandemic that killed nearly five million people through the Empire in 165–180 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] From Nerva to Marcus Aurelius, the empire achieved an unprecedented status.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The powerful influence of laws and manners had gradually cemented the union of the provinces.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] All the citizens enjoyed and abused the advantages of wealth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The image of a free constitution was preserved with decent reverence.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman senate appeared to possess the sovereign authority, and devolved on the emperors all the executive powers of government.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Gibbon declared the rule of these "Five Good Emperors" the golden era of the Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] During this time, Rome reached its greatest territorial extent.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius, became emperor after his father's death.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He is not counted as one of the Five Good Emperors, due to his direct kinship with the latter emperor; in addition, he was militarily passive.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus was killed by a conspiracy involving Quintus Aemilius Laetus and his wife Marcia in late 192 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The following year is known as the Year of the Five Emperors, during which Helvius Pertinax, Didius Julianus, Pescennius Niger, Clodius Albinus and Septimius Severus held the imperial dignity.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Pertinax, a member of the senate who had been one of Marcus Aurelius's right-hand men, was the choice of Laetus, and he ruled vigorously and judiciously.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Laetus soon became jealous and instigated Pertinax's murder by the Praetorian Guard, who then auctioned the empire to the highest bidder, Didius Julianus, for 25,000 sesterces per man.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The people of Rome were appalled and appealed to the frontier legions to save them.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The legions of three frontier provinces—Britannia, Pannonia Superior, and Syria—resented being excluded from the "donative" and replied by declaring their individual generals to be emperor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Lucius Septimius Severus Geta, the Pannonian commander, bribed the opposing forces, pardoned the Praetorian Guards and installed himself as emperor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He and his successors governed with the legions' support.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The changes on coinage and military expenditures were the root of the financial crisis that marked the Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Severus was enthroned after invading Rome and having Didius Julianus killed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Severus attempted to revive totalitarianism and, addressing the Roman people and Senate, praised the severity and cruelty of Marius and Sulla, which worried the senators.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia invaded Roman territory, Severus successfully waged war against that country.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Notwithstanding this military success, Severus failed in invading Hatra, a rich Arabian city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Severus killed his legate, who was gaining respect from the legions; and his soldiers fell victim to famine.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After this disastrous campaign, he withdrew.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Severus also intended to vanquish the whole of Britannia.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] To achieve this, he waged war against the Caledonians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] However, he became ill and died in 211 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His sons Caracalla and Geta were made emperors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Caracalla had his brother, a youth, assassinated in his mother's arms, and may have murdered 20,000 of Geta's followers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He continued Severus' policy and gained respect from the legions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Knowing that the citizens of Alexandria disliked him and were denigrating his character, Caracalla served a banquet for its notable citizens, after which his soldiers killed all the guests.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] From the security of the temple of Sarapis, he then directed an indiscriminate slaughter of Alexandria's people.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 212, he issued the Edict of Caracalla, giving full Roman citizenship to all free men living in the Empire, with the exception of the *dediticii*, people who had become subject to Rome through surrender in war, and freed slaves.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Mary Beard points to the edict as a fundamental turning point, after which *Rome* was "effectively a new state masquerading under an old name".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus conspired to have Caracalla assassinated by one of his soldiers during a pilgrimage to the Temple of the Moon in Carrhae, in 217 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus assumed power, but soon removed himself from Rome to the east and Antioch.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His brief reign ended in 218, when the youngster Bassianus, high priest of the temple of the Sun at Emesa, and supposedly illegitimate son of Caracalla, was declared Emperor by the disaffected soldiers of Macrinus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted the name of Antoninus but history has named him after his Sun god Elagabalus, represented on Earth in the form of a large black stone.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] An incompetent and lascivious ruler, Elagabalus adopted his cousin Severus Alexander, as Caesar, but subsequently grew jealous and attempted to assassinate him.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] However, the Praetorian guard preferred Alexander, murdered Elagabalus, dragged his mutilated corpse through the streets of Rome, and threw it into the Tiber.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Alexander waged war against many foes, including the revitalised Persia and also the Germanic peoples, who invaded Gaul.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His losses generated dissatisfaction among his soldiers, and some of them murdered him during his Germanic campaign in 235 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] A disastrous scenario emerged after the death of Alexander Severus: the Roman state was plagued by civil wars, external invasions, political chaos, pandemics and economic depression.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The old Roman values had fallen, and Mithraism and Christianity had begun to spread through the populace.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Emperors were no longer men linked with nobility; they usually were born in lower-classes of distant parts of the Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] These men rose to prominence through military ranks, and became emperors through civil wars.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] There were 26 emperors in a 49-year period, a signal of political instability.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Maximinus Thrax was the first ruler of that time, governing for just three years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Others ruled just for a few months, like Gordian I, Gordian II, Balbinus and Hostilian.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The population and the frontiers were abandoned, since the emperors were mostly concerned with defeating rivals and establishing their power.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The economy also suffered: massive military expenditures from the Severi caused a devaluation of Roman coins.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Hyperinflation came at this time as well.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Plague of Cyprian broke out in 250 and killed a huge portion of the population.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 260 AD, the provinces of Syria Palaestina, Asia Minor and Egypt separated from the rest of the Roman state to form the Palmyrene Empire, ruled by Queen Zenobia and centered on Palmyra.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year the Gallic Empire was created by Postumus, retaining Britannia and Gaul.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] These countries separated from Rome after the capture of emperor Valerian by the Sassanids of Persia, the first Roman ruler to be captured by his enemies; it was a humiliating fact for the Romans.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis began to recede during the reigns of Claudius Gothicus (268–270), who defeated the Gothic invaders, and Aurelian (271–275), who reconquered both the Gallic and Palmyrene Empires.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis was overcome during the reign of Diocletian.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 284 AD, Diocletian was hailed as Imperator by the eastern army.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian healed the empire from the crisis, by political and economic shifts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] A new form of government was established: the Tetrarchy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Empire was divided among four emperors, two in the West and two in the East.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The first tetrarchs were Diocletian (in the East), Maximian (in the West), and two junior emperors, Galerius (in the East) and Flavius Constantius (in the West).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] To adjust the economy, Diocletian made several tax reforms.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian expelled the Persians who plundered Syria and conquered some barbarian tribes with Maximian.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted many behaviours of Eastern monarchs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Anyone in the presence of the emperor had now to prostrate himself—a common act in the East, but never practised in Rome before.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian did not use a disguised form of Republic, as the other emperors since Augustus had done.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Between 290 and 330, half a dozen new capitals had been established by the members of the Tetrarchy, officially or not: Antioch, Nicomedia, Thessalonike, Sirmium, Milan, and Trier.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian was also responsible for a significant Christian persecution.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 303 he and Galerius started the persecution and ordered the destruction of all the Christian churches and scripts and forbade Christian worship.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian abdicated in 305 AD together with Maximian, thus, he was the first Roman emperor to resign.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] His reign ended the traditional form of imperial rule, the Principate (from princeps) and started the Tetrarchy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine assumed the empire as a tetrarch in 306.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He conducted many wars against the other tetrarchs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 313, he issued the Edict of Milan, which granted liberty for Christians to profess their religion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine was converted to Christianity, enforcing the Christian faith.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He began the Christianization of the Empire and of Europe—a process concluded by the Catholic Church in the Middle Ages.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] He was defeated by the Franks and the Alamanni during 306–308.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 324 he defeated another tetrarch, Licinius, and controlled all the empire, as it was before Diocletian.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] To celebrate his victories and Christianity's relevance, he rebuilt Byzantium and renamed it Nova Roma ("New Rome"); but the city soon gained the informal name of Constantinople ("City of Constantine").
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The reign of Julian, who under the influence of his adviser Mardonius attempted to restore Classical Roman and Hellenistic religion, only briefly interrupted the succession of Christian emperors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Constantinople served as a new capital for the Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In fact, Rome had lost its central importance since the Crisis of the Third Century—Mediolanum was the western capital from 286 to 330, until the reign of Honorius, when Ravenna was made capital, in the 5th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine's administrative and monetary reforms, that reunited the Empire under one emperor, and rebuilt the city of Byzantium, as Constantinopolis Nova Roma, changed the high period of the ancient world.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the late 4th and 5th centuries the Western Empire entered a critical stage which terminated with the fall of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The next emperor, Theodosius I (379–395), gave even more force to the Christian faith, and after his death, the Empire was divided into the Eastern Roman Empire, ruled by Arcadius and the Western Roman Empire, commanded by Honorius, both of which were Theodosius' sons.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The situation became more critical in 408, after the death of Stilicho, a general who tried to reunite the Empire and repel barbarian invasion in the early years of the 5th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 410, the Theodosian dynasty saw the Visigoths sack Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] During the 5th century, the Western Empire experienced a significant reduction of its territory.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Vandals conquered North Africa, the Visigoths claimed the southern part of Gaul, Gallaecia was taken by the Suebi, Britannia was abandoned by the central government, and the Empire suffered further from the invasions of Attila, chief of the Huns.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] General Orestes refused to meet the demands of the barbarian "allies" who now formed the army, and tried to expel them from Italy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Unhappy with this, their chieftain Odoacer defeated and killed Orestes, invaded Ravenna and dethroned Romulus Augustus, son of Orestes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] This event of 476, usually marks the end of Classical antiquity and beginning of the Middle Ages.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman noble and former emperor Julius Nepos continued to rule as emperor from Dalmatia even after the deposition of Romulus Augustus until his death in 480.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Some historians consider him to be the last emperor of the Western Empire instead of Romulus Augustus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After 1200 years of independence and nearly 700 years as a great power, the rule of Rome in the West ended.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Various reasons for Rome's fall have been proposed, including loss of Republicanism, moral decay, military tyranny, class war, slavery, economic stagnation, environmental change, disease, the decline of the Roman race, as well as the inevitable ebb and flow that all civilisations experience.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Empire survived for almost 1000 years after the fall of its Western counterpart and became the most stable Christian realm during the Middle Ages.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] During the 6th century, Justinian reconquered the Italian peninsula from the Ostrogoths, North Africa from the Vandals, and southern Hispania from the Visigoths.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] But within a few years of Justinian's death, Byzantine possessions in Italy were greatly reduced by the Lombards who settled in the peninsula.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the east, partially due to the weakening effect of the Plague of Justinian as well as a series of mutually destructive wars against the Persian Sassanian Empire, the Byzantines were threatened by the rise of Islam.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Its followers rapidly brought about the conquest of the Levant, the conquest of North Africa and the conquest of Egypt during the Arab–Byzantine wars, and soon presented a direct threat to Constantinople.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the following century, the Arabs captured southern Italy and Sicily.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In the west, Slavic populations penetrated deep into the Balkans.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Byzantine Romans, however, managed to stop further Islamic expansion into their lands during the 8th century and, beginning in the 9th century, reclaimed parts of the conquered lands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] In 1000 AD, the Eastern Empire was at its height: Basil II reconquered Bulgaria and Armenia, and culture and trade flourished.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] However, soon after, this expansion was abruptly stopped in 1071 with the Byzantine defeat in the Battle of Manzikert.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The aftermath of this battle sent the empire into a protracted period of decline.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] Two decades of internal strife and Turkic invasions ultimately led Emperor Alexios I Komnenos to send a call for help to the Western European kingdoms in 1095.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The West responded with the Crusades, eventually resulting in the Sack of Constantinople by participants of the Fourth Crusade.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of Constantinople in 1204 fragmented what remained of the Empire into successor states; the ultimate victor was the Empire of Nicaea.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] After the recapture of Constantinople by Imperial forces, the Empire was little more than a Greek state confined to the Aegean coast.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p01] The Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire collapsed when Mehmed the Conqueror conquered Constantinople on 29 May 1453.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The imperial city of Rome was the largest urban center in the empire, with a population variously estimated from 450,000 to close to one million.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Around 20% of the population under jurisdiction of ancient Rome (25–40%, depending on the standards used, in Roman Italy) lived in innumerable urban centers, with population of 10,000 and more and several military settlements, a very high rate of urbanisation by pre-industrial standards.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Most of those centers had a forum, temples, and other buildings similar to Rome's.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The average life expectancy in the Middle Empire was about 26–28 years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The roots of the legal principles and practices of the ancient Romans may be traced to the Law of the Twelve Tables promulgated in 449 BC and to the codification of law issued by order of Emperor Justinian I around 530 AD (see *Corpus Juris Civilis*).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law as preserved in Justinian's codes continued into the Byzantine Roman Empire, and formed the basis of similar codifications in continental Western Europe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman law continued, in a broader sense, to be applied throughout most of Europe until the end of the 17th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The major divisions of the law of ancient Rome, as contained within the Justinian and Theodosian law codes, consisted of *Jus civile*, *Jus gentium*, and *Jus naturale*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus civile* ('citizen law') was the body of common laws that applied to Roman citizens.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Urbanus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The *Jus gentium* ('law of nations') was the body of common laws that applied to foreigners, and their dealings with Roman citizens.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] *Praetor Peregrinus*) were the people who had jurisdiction over cases involving citizens and foreigners.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] *Jus naturale* encompassed natural law, the body of laws that were considered common to all beings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society is largely viewed as hierarchical, with slaves (*servi*) at the bottom, freedmen (*liberti*) above them, and free-born citizens (*cives*) at the top.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The broadest, and earliest, division was between the patricians, who could trace their ancestry to one of the 100 patriarchs at the founding of the city, and the plebeians, who could not.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] This became less important in the later Republic, as some plebeian families became wealthy and entered politics, and some patrician families fell economically.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Anyone, patrician or plebeian, who could count a consul as his ancestor was a noble (*nobilis*); a man who was the first of his family to hold the consulship, such as Marius or Cicero, was known as a *novus homo* ('new man') and ennobled his descendants.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Patrician ancestry, however, still conferred considerable prestige, and many religious offices remained restricted to patricians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] A class division originally based on military service became more important.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Membership of these classes was determined periodically by the censors, according to property.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The wealthiest were the Senatorial class, who dominated politics and command of the army.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Next came the equestrians (*equites*, sometimes translated "knights"), originally those who could afford a warhorse, and who formed a powerful mercantile class.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Several further classes, originally based on the military equipment their members could afford, followed, with the *proletarii*, citizens who had no property other than their children, at the bottom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Before the reforms of Marius they were ineligible for military service and are often described as being just above freed slaves in wealth and prestige.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Voting power in the Republic depended on class.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Citizens were enrolled in voting "tribes", but the tribes of the richer classes had fewer members than the poorer ones, all the *proletarii* being enrolled in a single tribe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Voting was done in class order, from top down, and stopped as soon as most of the tribes had been reached, so the poorer classes were often unable to cast their votes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Women in ancient Rome shared some basic rights with their male counterparts, but were not fully regarded as citizens and were thus not allowed to vote or take part in politics.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] At the same time the limited rights of women were gradually expanded (due to emancipation) and women reached freedom from *pater familias*, gained property rights and even had more juridical rights than their husbands, but still no voting rights, and were absent from politics.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Allied foreign cities were often given the Latin Rights, an intermediary level between full citizens and foreigners (*peregrini*), which gave their citizens rights under Roman law and allowed their leading magistrates to become full Roman citizens.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] While there were varying degrees of Latin rights, the main division was between those *cum suffragio* ('with vote'; enrolled in a Roman tribe and able to take part in the *comitia tributa*) and *sine suffragio* ('without vote'; could not take part in Roman politics).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, there were no public schools, so boys were taught to read and write by their parents, or by educated slaves, called *paedagogi*, usually of Greek origin.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The primary aim of education during this period was to train young men in agriculture, warfare, Roman traditions, and public affairs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Young boys learned much about civic life by accompanying their fathers to religious and political functions, including the Senate for the sons of nobles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The sons of nobles were apprenticed to a prominent political figure at the age of 16, and campaigned with the army from the age of 17.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Educational practices were modified after the conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms in the 3rd century BC and the resulting Greek influence, although Roman educational practices were still much different from Greek ones.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning at age 12, students went to secondary schools, where the teacher (now called a *grammaticus*) taught them about Greek and Roman literature.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] At the age of 16, some students went on to rhetoric school (where the teacher, usually Greek, was called a *rhetor*).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Education at this level prepared students for legal careers, and required that the students memorise the laws of Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Initially, Rome was ruled by kings, who were elected from each of Rome's major tribes in turn.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The exact nature of the king's power is uncertain.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] He may have held near-absolute power, or may have merely been the chief executive of the Senate and the people.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In military matters, the king's authority (*Imperium*) was likely absolute.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] He was also the head of the state religion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The class struggles of the Roman Republic resulted in an unusual mixture of democracy and oligarchy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The word republic comes from the Latin *res publica*, which literally translates to 'public business'.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman laws traditionally could only be passed by a vote of the Popular assembly (Comitia Tributa).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Likewise, candidates for public positions had to run for election by the people.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] However, the Roman Senate represented an oligarchic institution, which acted as an advisory body.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the Republic, the Senate held actual authority (*auctoritas*), but no real legislative power; it was technically only an advisory council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] However, as the Senators were individually very influential, it was difficult to accomplish anything against the collective will of the Senate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] New senators were chosen from among the most accomplished patricians by censors (*Censura*), who could also remove a senator from his office if he was found "morally corrupt".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Later, under the reforms of the dictator Sulla, quaestors were made automatic members of the Senate, though most of his reforms did not survive.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Republic had no fixed bureaucracy, and collected taxes through the practice of tax farming.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Government positions such as quaestor, aedile, or praefect were funded by the office-holder.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] To prevent any citizen from gaining too much power, new magistrates were elected annually and had to share power with a colleague.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] For example, under normal conditions, the highest authority was held by two consuls.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In an emergency, a temporary dictator could be appointed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the Republic, the administrative system was revised several times to comply with new demands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the end, it proved inefficient for controlling the ever-expanding dominion of Rome, contributing to the establishment of the Roman Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Empire, the pretense of a republican form of government was maintained.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman emperor was portrayed as only a *princeps*, or 'first citizen', and the Senate gained legislative power and all legal authority previously held by the popular assemblies.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] However, the rule of the Emperors became increasingly autocratic, and the Senate was reduced to an advisory body appointed by the Emperor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire did not inherit a set bureaucracy from the Republic, since the Republic did not have any permanent governmental structures apart from the Senate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor appointed assistants and advisers, but the state lacked many institutions, such as a centrally planned budget.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have cited this as a significant reason for the decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] 500 BC) was, like those of other contemporary city-states influenced by Greek civilisation, a citizen *militia* that practised hoplite tactics.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] It was small and organised in five classes (in parallel to the *comitia centuriata*, the body of citizens organised politically), with three providing hoplites and two providing light infantry.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The early Roman army was tactically limited and its stance during this period was essentially defensive.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] By the 3rd century BC, the Romans abandoned the hoplite formation in favour of a more flexible system in which smaller groups of 120 (or sometimes 60) men called '*maniples* could manoeuvre more independently on the battlefield.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Thirty maniples arranged in three lines with supporting troops constituted a legion, totalling between 4,000 and 5,000 men.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The early Republican legion consisted of five sections: manipular heavy infantry (*hastati*, *principes* and *triarii*), a force of light infantry (*velites*), and the cavalry (*equites*).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] With the new organisation came a new orientation toward the offensive and a much more aggressive posture toward adjoining city-states.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Until the late Republican period, the typical legionary was a property-owning citizen farmer from a rural area (an *adsiduus*) who served for particular (often annual) campaigns, and who supplied his own equipment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] After 200 BC, economic conditions in rural areas deteriorated as manpower needs increased, so that the property qualifications for compulsory service were gradually reduced.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning in the 3rd century BC, legionaries were paid a stipend.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] By the time of Augustus, the ideal of the citizen-soldier had been abandoned and the legions had become fully professional.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] At the end of the Civil War, Augustus reorganised Roman military forces, discharging soldiers and disbanding legions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] He retained 28 legions, distributed through the provinces of the Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During the Principate, the tactical organisation of the Army continued to evolve.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The *auxilia* remained independent cohorts, and legionary troops often operated as groups of cohorts rather than as full legions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] A new and versatile type of unit, the *cohortes equitatae*, combined cavalry and legionaries in a single formation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] They could be stationed at garrisons or outposts and could fight on their own as balanced small forces or combine with similar units as a larger, legion-sized force.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] This increase in organizational flexibility helped ensure the long-term success of Roman military forces.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Emperor Gallienus (253–268 AD) began a reorganisation that created the last military structure of the late Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Withdrawing some legionaries from the fixed bases on the border, Gallienus created mobile forces (the *comitatenses*, or field armies) and stationed them behind and at some distance from the borders as a strategic reserve.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The border troops (*limitanei*) stationed at fixed bases continued to be the first line of defence.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of the field army were regimental; *legiones* or *auxilia* for infantry and *vexillationes* for cavalry.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Nominal strengths may have been 1,200 men for infantry regiments and 600 for cavalry, but actual troop levels could have been much lower—800 infantry and 400 cavalry.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Many infantry and cavalry regiments operated in pairs under the command of a *comes*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Field armies included regiments recruited from allied tribes and known as *foederati*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] By 400 AD, *foederati* regiments had become permanently established units of the Roman army, paid and equipped by the Empire, led by a Roman tribune and used just as Roman units were used.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Empire also used groups of barbarians to fight along with the legions as allies without integration into the field armies, under overall command of a Roman general, but led by their own officers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Military leadership evolved over the course of the history of Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Under the monarchy, the hoplite armies were led by the kings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During the early and middle Roman Republic, military forces were under the command of one of the two elected consuls for the year.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During the later Republic, members of the Roman Senatorial elite, as part of the normal sequence of elected public offices known as the *cursus honorum*, would have served first as *quaestor* (often posted as deputies to field commanders), then as *praetor*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Following the end of a term as praetor or consul, a Senator might be appointed by the Senate as a *propraetor* or *proconsul* (depending on the highest office held before) to govern a foreign province.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Under Augustus, whose most important political priority was to place the military under a permanent and unitary command, the Emperor was the legal commander of each legion but exercised that command through a *legatus* (legate) he appointed from the Senatorial elite.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During the later stages of the Imperial period (beginning perhaps with Diocletian), the Augustan model was abandoned.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Provincial governors were stripped of military authority, and command of the armies in a group of provinces was given to generals (*duces*) appointed by the Emperor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] These were no longer members of the Roman elite but men who came up through the ranks and had seen much practical soldiering.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] With increasing frequency, these men attempted (sometimes successfully) to usurp the positions of the Emperors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Decreased resources, increasing political chaos and civil war eventually left the Western Empire vulnerable to attack and takeover by neighbouring barbarian peoples.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Less is known about the Roman navy than the Roman army.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Prior to the middle of the 3rd century BC, officials known as *duumviri navales* commanded a fleet of twenty ships used mainly to control piracy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] This fleet was given up in 278 AD and replaced by allied forces.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The First Punic War required that Rome build large fleets, and it did so largely with the assistance of and financing from allies.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] This reliance on allies continued to the end of the Roman Republic.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The quinquereme was the main warship on both sides of the Punic Wars and remained the mainstay of Roman naval forces until replaced by the time of Caesar Augustus by lighter and more manoeuvrable vessels.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Ships were commanded by a *navarch*, a rank equal to a centurion, who was usually not a citizen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Potter suggests that because the fleet was dominated by non-Romans, the navy was considered non-Roman and allowed to atrophy in times of peace.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Information suggests that by the time of the late Empire (350 AD), the Roman navy comprised several fleets including warships and merchant vessels for transportation and supply.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Warships were oared sailing galleys with three to five banks of oarsmen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Fleet bases included such ports as Ravenna, Arles, Aquilea, Misenum and the mouth of the Somme River in the West and Alexandria and Rhodes in the East.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Flotillas of small river craft (*classes*) were part of the *limitanei* (border troops) during this period, based at fortified river harbours along the Rhine and the Danube.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] That prominent generals commanded both armies and fleets suggests that naval forces were treated as auxiliaries to the army and not as an independent service.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The details of command structure and fleet strengths during this period are not well known, although fleets were commanded by prefects.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome commanded a vast area of land, with tremendous natural and human resources.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] As such, Rome's economy remained focused on farming and trade.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Agricultural free trade changed the Italian landscape, and by the 1st century BC, vast grape and olive estates had supplanted the yeoman farmers, who were unable to match the imported grain price.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The annexation of Egypt, Sicily and Tunisia in North Africa provided a continuous supply of grains.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In turn, olive oil and wine were Italy's main exports.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Two-tier crop rotation was practised, but farm productivity was low.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Industrial and manufacturing activities were small.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The largest such activities were the mining and quarrying of stones, which provided basic construction materials for the buildings of that period.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In manufacturing, production was on a relatively small scale, and generally consisted of workshops and small factories that employed at most dozens of workers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] However, some brick factories employed hundreds of workers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The economy of the early Republic was largely based on smallholding and paid labour.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] However, foreign wars and conquests made slaves increasingly cheap and plentiful, and by the late Republic, the economy was largely dependent on slave labour for both skilled and unskilled work.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Slaves are estimated to have constituted around 20% of the Roman Empire's population at this time and 40% in the city of Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Only in the Roman Empire, when the conquests stopped and the prices of slaves increased, did hired labour become more economical than slave ownership.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Although barter was used in ancient Rome, and often used in tax collection, Rome had a very developed coinage system, with brass, bronze, and precious metal coins in circulation throughout the Empire and beyond—some have even been discovered in India.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Before the 3rd century BC, copper was traded by weight, measured in unmarked lumps, across central Italy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The original copper coins (*as*) had a face value of one Roman pound of copper, but weighed less.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, Roman money's utility as a unit of exchange consistently exceeded its intrinsic value as metal.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] After Nero began debasing the silver denarius, its legal value was an estimated one-third greater than its intrinsic value.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Horses were expensive and other pack animals were slower.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Mass trade on the Roman roads connected military posts, where Roman markets were centered.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] As a result, there was transport of commodities between Roman regions, but increased with the rise of Roman maritime trade in the 2nd century BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During that period, a trading vessel took less than a month to complete a trip from Gades to Alexandria via Ostia, spanning the entire length of the Mediterranean.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Transport by sea was around 60 times cheaper than by land, so the volume for such trips was much larger.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Some economists consider the Roman Empire a market economy, similar in its degree of capitalistic practices to the 17th-century Netherlands and 18th-century England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The basic units of Roman society were households and families.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Groups of households connected through the male line formed a family (*gens*), based on blood ties, a common ancestry or adoption.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During the Republic, some powerful families, or *Gentes Maiores*, came to dominate political life.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Families were headed by their oldest male citizen, the *pater familias* (father of the family), who held lawful authority (*patria potestas*, 'father's power') over wives, sons, daughters, and slaves of the household, and the family's wealth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The extreme expressions of this power—the selling or killing of family members for moral or civil offences, including simple disobedience—were very rarely exercised, and were forbidden in the Imperial era.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] A *pater familias* had moral and legal duties towards all family members.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Even the most despotic *pater familias* was expected to consult senior members of his household and *gens* over matters that affected the family's well-being and reputation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, such matters were regarded as outside the purview of the state and its magistrates; under the emperors, they were increasingly subject to state interference and legislation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Once accepted into their birth family by their fathers, children were potential heirs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] They could not be lawfully given away, or sold into slavery.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] If parents were unable to care for their child, or if its paternity was in doubt, they could resort to infant exposure (Boswell translates this as being "offered" up to care by the gods or strangers).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] If a deformed or sickly newborn was patently "unfit to live", killing it was a duty of the *pater familias*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] A citizen father who exposed a healthy freeborn child was not punished, but automatically lost his *potestas* over that child.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Abandoned children were sometimes adopted; some would have been sold into slavery.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Slavery was near-ubiquitous and almost universally accepted.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the early Republic, citizens in debt were allowed to sell their labour, and perhaps their sons, to their debtor in a limited form of slavery called *nexum* but this was abolished in the middle Republic.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Freedom was considered a natural and proper state for citizens; slaves could be lawfully freed, with consent and support of their owners, and still serve their owners' family and financial interests, as freedmen or freed women.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] This was the basis of the client-patron relationship, one of the most important features of Rome's economy and society.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In law, a *pater familias* held *potestas* over his adult sons with their own households.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] This could give rise to legal anomalies, such as adult sons also having the status of minors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] No man could be considered a *pater familias*, nor could he truly hold property under law, while his own father lived.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During Rome's early history, married daughters came under the control (*manus*) of their husbands' *pater familias*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] By the late Republic, most married women retained lawful connection to their birth family, though any children from the marriage belonged to her husband's family.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The mother or an elderly relative often raised both boys and girls.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman moralists held that marriage and child-raising fulfilled a basic duty to family, *gens*, and the state.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Fathers usually began seeking husbands for their daughters when these reached an age between twelve and fourteen, but most commoner-class women stayed single until their twenties, and in general seem to have been far more independent than wives of the elite.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Divorce required the consent of one party, along with the return of any dowry.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Both parents had power over their children during their minority and adulthood, but husbands had much less control over their wives.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman citizen women held a restricted form of citizenship; they could not vote but were protected by law.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] They ran families, could own and run businesses, own and cultivate land, write their own wills, and plead in court on their own behalf, or on behalf of others, all under dispensation of the courts and the nominal supervision of a senior male relative.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The latter was much resented, and the former had seemingly negligible results.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Aristocratic women seem to have been increasingly disinclined to childbearing.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman hours were counted ordinally from dawn to dawn.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, if sunrise was at 6 am, then 6 to 7 am was called the 'first hour'.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Midday was called *meridies*, and it is from this word that the terms *am* (*ante meridiem*) and *pm* (*post meridiem*) stem.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The English word "noon" comes from *nona* ('ninth (hour)'), which referred to 3 pm in ancient Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had clocks (*horologia*), which included giant public sundials (*solaria*) and water clocks (*clepsydrae*).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman week originally had eight days, which were identified by letters A to H, with the eighth day being the *nundinum*, or market day, a kind of weekend when farmers sold their produce on the streets.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The seven-day week, introduced from the East during the early Empire, was officially adopted during the reign of Constantine.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Romans named week days after celestial bodies from at least the 1st century AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman year originally had ten months from Martius (March) to December, with the winter period not included in the calendar.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The first four months were named after gods (Martius, Aprilis, Maius, Junius) and the others were numbered (Quintilis, Sextilis, September, October, November, and December).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Numa Pompilius, the second king of Rome (716–673 BC), is said to have introduced the months of January and February, both also named after gods, beginning the 12-month calendar still in use today.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In 44 BC, the month Quintilis was renamed to Julius (July) after Julius Caesar and in 8 BC, Sextilis was renamed to Augustus (August) after Augustus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans had several ways of tracking years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] One widespread way was the consular dating, which identified years by the two consuls who ruled each year.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, introduced in the late 3rd century AD, was counting years from the *indictio*, a 15-year period based on the announcement of the delivery of food and other goods to the government.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Another way, less popular but more similar to present day, was *ab urbe condita*, which counted years from the mythical foundation of Rome in 753 BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Life in ancient Rome revolved around the city of Rome, located on seven hills.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The city had a vast number of monumental structures like the Colosseum, the Trajan's Forum and the Pantheon.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] It had theatres, gymnasiums, marketplaces, functional sewers, bath complexes complete with libraries and shops, and fountains with fresh drinking water supplied by hundreds of miles of aqueducts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Throughout the territory under the control of ancient Rome, residential architecture ranged from modest houses to country villas.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, there were imperial residences on Palatine Hill.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The low plebeian and middle equestrian classes lived in the city center, packed into apartments, or insulae, which were almost like modern ghettos.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] These areas, often built by upper class property owners to rent, were often centred upon collegia or taberna.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] These people, provided with a free supply of grain, and entertained by gladiatorial games, were enrolled as clients of patrons among the upper class patricians, whose assistance they sought and whose interests they upheld.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The native language of the Romans was Latin, an Italic language the grammar of which relies little on word order, conveying meaning through a system of affixes attached to word stems.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Its alphabet was based on the Etruscan alphabet, which was in turn based on the Greek alphabet.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Speakers of Latin could understand both until the 7th century when spoken Latin began to diverge so much that 'Classical' or 'Good Latin' had to be learned as a second language.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] While Latin remained the main written language of the Roman Empire, Greek came to be the language spoken by the well-educated elite, as most of the literature studied by Romans was written in Greek.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Most of the emperors were bilingual but had a preference for Latin in the public sphere for political reasons, a practice that first started during the Punic wars.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the eastern part of the Roman Empire (and later the Eastern Roman Empire), Latin was never able to replace Greek, a legacy of the Hellenistic period.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Justinian would be the last emperor to use Latin in government and marks when Greek officially took over.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The expansion of the Roman Empire spread Latin throughout Europe, and Vulgar Latin evolved into many distinct Romance languages.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Archaic Roman religion, at least concerning the gods, was made up not of written narratives, but rather of complex interrelations between gods and humans.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Unlike in Greek mythology, the gods were not personified, but were vaguely defined sacred spirits called *numina*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Romans also believed that every person, place or thing had its own *genius*, or divine soul.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During the Roman Republic, Roman religion was organised under a strict system of priestly offices, which were held by men of senatorial rank.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The College of Pontifices was uppermost body in this hierarchy, and its chief priest, the *Pontifex Maximus*, was the head of the state religion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Flamens took care of the cults of various gods, while augurs were trusted with taking the auspices.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The sacred king took on the religious responsibilities of the deposed kings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman Empire, deceased emperors who had ruled well were deified by their successors and the Senate. and the formalised imperial cult became increasingly prominent.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] As contact with the Greeks increased, the old Roman gods became increasingly associated with Greek gods.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Under the Empire, the Romans absorbed the mythologies of their conquered subjects, often leading to situations in which the temples and priests of traditional Italian deities existed side by side with those of foreign gods.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Beginning with Emperor Nero in the 1st century AD, Roman official policy towards Christianity was negative, and at some point, being a Christian could be punishable by death.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Under Emperor Diocletian, the persecution of Christians reached its peak.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] However, it became an officially supported religion in the Roman state under Diocletian's successor, Constantine I, with the signing of the Edict of Milan in 313, and quickly became dominant.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] All religions except Christianity were prohibited in 391 AD by an edict of Emperor Theodosius I.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Like many ancient cultures, concepts of ethics and morality, while sharing some commonalities with modern society, differed greatly in several important ways.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Because ancient civilisations like Rome were under constant threat of attack from marauding tribes, their culture was necessarily militaristic with martial skills being a prized attribute.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Whereas modern societies consider compassion a virtue, Roman society considered compassion a vice, a moral defect.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] One of the primary purposes of the gladiatorial games was to inoculate Roman citizens from this weakness.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Romans instead prized virtues such as courage and conviction (*virtus*), a sense of duty to one's people, moderation and avoiding excess (*moderatio*), forgiveness and understanding (*clementia*), fairness (*severitas*), and loyalty (*pietas*).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman society had well-established and restrictive norms related to sexuality, though as with many societies, the lion's share of the responsibilities fell on women.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Women were generally expected to be monogamous having only a single husband during their life (*univira*), though this was much less regarded by the elite, especially under the empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Women were expected to be modest in public avoiding any provocative appearance and to demonstrate absolute fidelity to their husbands (*pudicitia*).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Wearing a veil was a common expectation to preserve modesty.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Sex outside of marriage was generally frowned upon for men and women and was made illegal during the imperial period.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Nevertheless, prostitution was an accepted and regulated practice.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Public demonstrations of death, violence, and brutality were used as a source of entertainment in Roman communities; however it was also a way to maintain social order, demonstrate power, and signify communal unity.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman painting styles show Greek influences, and surviving examples are primarily frescoes used to adorn the walls and ceilings of country villas, though Roman literature includes mentions of paintings on wood, ivory, and other materials.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Several examples of Roman painting have been found at Pompeii, and from these art historians divide the history of Roman painting into four periods.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The first style of Roman painting was practised from the early 2nd century BC to the early- or mid-1st century BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] It was mainly composed of imitations of marble and masonry, though sometimes including depictions of mythological characters.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The second style began during the early 1st century BC and attempted to depict realistically three-dimensional architectural features and landscapes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The third style occurred during the reign of Augustus (27 BC – 14 AD), and rejected the realism of the second style in favour of simple ornamentation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] A small architectural scene, landscape, or abstract design was placed in the center with a monochrome background.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The fourth style, which began in the 1st century AD, depicted scenes from mythology, while retaining architectural details and abstract patterns.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Portrait sculpture used youthful and classical proportions, evolving later into a mixture of realism and idealism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During the Antonine and Severan periods, ornate hair and bearding, with deep cutting and drilling, became popular.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were also made in relief sculptures, usually depicting Roman victories.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman music was largely based on Greek music, and played an important part in many aspects of Roman life.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the Roman military, musical instruments such as the *tuba* (a long trumpet) or the *cornu* were used to give various commands, while the *buccina* (possibly a trumpet or horn) and the *lituus* (probably an elongated J-shaped instrument), were used in ceremonial capacities.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Music was used in the Roman amphitheatres between fights and in the *odea*, and in these settings is known to have featured the *cornu* and the *hydraulis* (a type of water organ).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Most religious rituals featured musical performances.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Some music historians believe that music was used at almost all public ceremonies.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The graffiti, brothels, paintings, and sculptures found in Pompeii and Herculaneum suggest that the Romans had a sex-saturated culture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Latin literature was, from its start, influenced heavily by Greek authors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Some of the earliest extant works are of historical epics telling the early military history of Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] As the Republic expanded, authors began to produce poetry, comedy, history, and tragedy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome's literary contributions are still recognised today and the works by ancient Roman authors were available in bookshops as well as in public and private libraries.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Many scholars and statesmen of ancient Rome cultivated private libraries that were used both as demonstrations of knowledge and displays of wealth and power.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Although Julius Caesar had intended to establish public libraries to further establish Rome as a great cultural center like Athens and Alexandria, he died before this was accomplished.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Caesar's former lieutenant, Gaius Asinius Pollio, took up the project and opened the first public library in Rome in the Atrium Libertatis.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Emperors Augustus, Tiberius, Vespasian, Domitian, and Trajan also founded or expanded public libraries in Rome during their reigns.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] These included the Ulpian Library in Trajan's Forum and libraries in the Temple of Apollo Palatinus, the Temple of Peace in the Roman Forum, the Temple of Divus Augustus, which was dedicated to Minerva when it was rebuilt under Emperor Domitian's orders.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] By the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the city of Rome had more than two dozen public libraries.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] As the Roman Empire spread, public libraries were established in other major cities and cultural centers including Ephesos, Athens, and Timgad.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Roman cuisine changed over the long duration of this ancient civilisation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Dietary habits were affected by the influence of Greek culture, the political changes from Kingdom to Republic to Empire, and the Empire's enormous expansion, which exposed Romans to many new, provincial culinary habits and cooking techniques.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the beginning the differences between social classes were relatively small, but disparities evolved with the Empire's growth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Men and women drank wine with their meals.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The ancient Roman diet included many items that are staples of modern Italian cooking.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] However, some foods now considered characteristic of modern Italian cuisine were not used.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In particular, spinach and eggplant (aubergine) were introduced later from the Arab world, and tomatoes, potatoes, capsicum peppers, and maize (the modern source of polenta) only appeared in Europe following the discovery of the New World and the Columbian Exchange.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans knew of rice, but it was very rarely available to them.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Butcher's meat such as beef was an uncommon luxury.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The most popular meat was pork, especially sausages.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Fish was more common than meat, with a sophisticated aquaculture and large-scale industries devoted to oyster farming.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also engaged in snail farming and oak grub farming.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Some fish were greatly esteemed and fetched high prices, such as mullet raised in the fishery at Cosa, and "elaborate means were invented to assure its freshness".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Traditionally, a breakfast called *ientaculum* was served at dawn.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] At mid-day to early afternoon, Romans ate *cena*, the main meal of the day, and at nightfall a light supper called *vesperna*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] With the increased importation of foreign foods, the *cena* grew larger in size and included a wider range of foods.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Thus, it gradually shifted to the evening, while the *vesperna* was abandoned completely over the course of the years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The mid-day meal *prandium* became a light meal to hold one over until *cena*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The toga, a common garment during the era of Julius Caesar, was gradually abandoned by all social classes of the Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] At the early 4th century, the toga had become just a garment worn by senators in Senate and ceremonial events.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] At the 4th century, the toga was replaced by the *paenula* (a garment similar to a poncho) as the everyday garment of the Romans, from the lower classes to the upper classes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Another garment that was popular among the Romans in the later years of the Western Roman Empire was the *pallium*, which was mostly worn by philosophers and scholars in general.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Due to external influences, mainly from the Germanic peoples, the Romans adopted tunics very similar to those used by the Germanic peoples with whom they interacted in the final years of the Western Empire, also adopted trousers and hats like the *pileus pannonicus*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] During the Late Empire, the *paludamentum* (a type of military clothing) was used only by the Emperor of Rome (since the reign of Augustus, the first emperor) while the dalmatic (also used by the Christian clergy) began to spread throughout the empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The youth of Rome had several forms of athletic play and exercise.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Play for boys was supposed to prepare them for active military service, such as jumping, wrestling, boxing, and racing.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the countryside, pastimes for the wealthy also included fishing and hunting.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also had several forms of ball playing, including one resembling handball.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Dice games, board games, and gamble games were popular pastimes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] For the wealthy, dinner parties presented an opportunity for entertainment, sometimes featuring music, dancing, and poetry readings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The majority, less well-off, sometimes enjoyed similar parties through clubs or associations, but for most Romans, recreational dining usually meant patronising taverns.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Children entertained themselves with toys and such games as leapfrog.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Public games and spectacles were sponsored by leading Romans who wished to advertise their generosity and court popular approval; in Rome or its provinces, this usually meant the emperor or his governors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Venues in Rome and the provinces were developed specifically for public games.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Rome's Colosseum was built in 70 AD under the Roman emperor Vespasian and opened in 80 AD to host other events and gladiatorial combats.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Gladiators sometimes fought to the death, but more often to an adjudicated victory, usually in keeping with the mood of the watching crowd.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Shows of exotic animals were popular in their own right; but sometimes animals were pitted against human beings, either armed professionals or unarmed criminals who had been condemned to public death.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Chariot racing was extremely popular among all classes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In Rome, these races were usually held at the Circus Maximus, which had been purpose-built for chariot and horse-racing and, as Rome's largest public place, was also used for festivals and animal shows.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Ancient Rome boasted impressive technological feats, using many advancements that were lost in the Middle Ages and not rivalled again until the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] An example of this is insulated glazing, which was not invented again until the 1930s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Many practical Roman innovations were adopted from earlier Greek designs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Advancements were often divided and based on craft.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Artisans guarded technologies as trade secrets.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Roman civil engineering and military engineering constituted a large part of Rome's technological superiority and legacy, and contributed to the construction of hundreds of roads, bridges, aqueducts, public baths, theatres and arenas.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Many monuments, such as the Colosseum, Pont du Gard, and Pantheon, remain as testaments to Roman engineering and culture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans were renowned for their architecture, which is grouped with Greek traditions into "Classical architecture".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Although there were many differences from Greek architecture, Rome borrowed heavily from Greece in adhering to strict, formulaic building designs and proportions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Aside from two new orders of columns, composite and Tuscan, and from the dome, which was derived from the Etruscan arch, Rome had relatively few architectural innovations until the end of the Republic.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] In the 1st century BC, Romans started to use Roman concrete widely.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Concrete was invented in the late 3rd century BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] It was a powerful cement derived from pozzolana, and soon supplanted marble as the chief Roman building material and allowed many daring architectural forms.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Also in the 1st century BC, Vitruvius wrote *De architectura*, possibly the first complete treatise on architecture in history.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also largely built using timber, causing a rapid decline of the woodlands surrounding Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] It is suggested that timber, around 4 metres (13 ft) long, came up to Rome via the Tiber River on ships travelling across the Mediterranean Sea from the confluence of the Saône and Rhône rivers in what is now the city of Lyon in present-day France.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] With solid foundations and good drainage, Roman roads were known for their durability and many segments of the Roman road system were still in use a thousand years after the fall of Rome.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The construction of a vast and efficient travel network throughout the Empire dramatically increased Rome's power and influence.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] They allowed Roman legions to be deployed rapidly, with predictable marching times between key points of the empire, no matter the season.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] These highways also had enormous economic significance, solidifying Rome's role as a trading crossroads—the origin of the saying "all roads lead to Rome".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Roman government maintained a system of way stations, known as the *cursus publicus*, and established a system of horse relays allowing a dispatch to travel up to 80 km (50 mi) a day.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans constructed numerous aqueducts to supply water to cities and industrial sites and to aid in their agriculture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] By the third century, the city of Rome was supplied by 11 aqueducts with a combined length of 450 km (280 mi).
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] The Romans also made major advancements in sanitation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Romans were particularly famous for their public baths, called *thermae*, which were used for both hygienic and social purposes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Many Roman houses had flush toilets and indoor plumbing, and a complex sewer system, the *Cloaca Maxima*, was used to drain the local marshes and carry waste into the Tiber.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p02] Some historians have speculated that lead pipes in the sewer and plumbing systems led to widespread lead poisoning, which contributed to fall of Rome; however, lead content would have been minimised.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] Ancient Rome is the progenitor of Western civilisation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] The customs, religion, law, technology, architecture, political system, military, literature, languages, alphabet, government and many factors and aspects of western civilisation are all inherited from Roman advancements.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] The rediscovery of Roman culture revitalised Western civilisation, playing a role in the Renaissance and the Age of Enlightenment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] The two longest ancient accounts of the Roman history, the histories of Livy and Dionysius of Halicarnassus, were composed 500 years later than the date for the founding of the republic and 200 years from the defeat of Hannibal.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] Although there has been a diversity of works on ancient Roman history, many of them are lost.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] As a result of this loss, there are gaps in Roman history, which are filled by unreliable works, such as the **Historia Augusta**.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] Caesar wrote his own accounts of his military campaigns in Gaul and during the Civil War in part to impress his contemporaries.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] In the Empire, the biographies of famous men and early emperors flourished, examples being *The Twelve Caesars* of Suetonius, and Plutarch's *Parallel Lives*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] Other major works of Imperial times were that of Livy and Tacitus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] Interest in studying, and idealising, ancient Rome became prevalent during the Italian Renaissance.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] Edward Gibbon's *The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* "began the modern study of Roman history in the English-speaking world".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] Barthold Georg Niebuhr was a founder of the examination of ancient Roman history and wrote *The Roman History*, tracing the period until the First Punic War.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] During the Napoleonic, *The History of Romans* by Victor Duruy highlighted the Caesarean period popular at the time.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/ancient-rome-p03] *History of Rome*, *Roman constitutional law* and *Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum*, all by Theodor Mommsen, became milestones.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The **Antonine Wall** (Latin: *Vallum Antonini*) was a turf fortification on stone foundations, built by the Romans across what is now the Central Belt of Scotland, between the Firth of Clyde and the Firth of Forth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Built some twenty years after Hadrian's Wall to the south, and intended to supersede it, while it was garrisoned it was the northernmost frontier barrier of the Roman Empire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] It spanned approximately 63 kilometres (39 miles) and was about 3 metres (10 feet) high and 5 metres (16 feet) wide.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Lidar scans have been carried out to establish the length of the wall and the Roman distance units used.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Security was bolstered by a deep ditch on the northern side.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] It is thought that there was a wooden palisade on top of the turf.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The barrier was the second of two "great walls" created by the Romans in Great Britain in the second century AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Its ruins are less evident than those of the better-known and longer Hadrian's Wall to the south, primarily because the turf and wood wall has largely weathered away, unlike its stone-built southern predecessor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Construction began in AD 142 at the order of Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Estimates of how long it took to complete vary widely, with six and twelve years most commonly proposed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Antoninus Pius never visited Britain, unlike his predecessor Hadrian.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Pressure from the Caledonians probably led Antoninus to send the empire's troops farther north.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was protected by 16 forts with small fortlets between them; troop movement was facilitated by a road linking all the sites known as the Military Way.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The soldiers who built the wall commemorated the construction and their struggles with the Caledonians with decorative slabs, twenty of which survive.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The wall was abandoned only eight years after completion, and the garrisons relocated rearward to Hadrian's Wall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Most of the wall and its associated fortifications have been destroyed over time, but some remains are visible.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Many of these have come under the care of Historic Environment Scotland and the UNESCO World Heritage Committee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius ordered the construction of the Antonine Wall around 142.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] Quintus Lollius Urbicus, governor of Roman Britain at the time, initially supervised the effort, which may have taken as long as twelve years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The wall stretches 63 kilometres (39 miles) from Old Kilpatrick in West Dunbartonshire on the Firth of Clyde to Carriden near Bo'ness on the Firth of Forth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The wall was intended to extend Roman territory and dominance by replacing Hadrian's Wall 160 kilometres (100 miles) to the south, as the frontier of *Britannia*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] But while the Romans did establish forts and temporary camps further north of the Antonine Wall in order to protect their routes to northern Britain, they did not conquer the Caledonians, and the Antonine Wall suffered many attacks.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The Romans called the land north of the wall *Caledonia*, though in some contexts the term may refer to the whole area north of Hadrian's Wall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The land north of the Antonine Wall became known as Albany after the settlement of the Gaels in the 6th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was shorter than Hadrian's Wall and built of turf on a stone foundation, but it was still an impressive achievement.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] It was also a simpler fortification than Hadrian's Wall insofar as it did not have a subsidiary ditch system (Vallum) behind it to the south.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] As built, the wall was typically a bank, about three metres (10 feet) high, made of layered turves and occasionally earth with a wide ditch on the north side, and a military way on the south.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The stone foundations and wing walls of the original forts on the Antonine Wall demonstrate that the original plan was to build a stone wall similar to Hadrian's Wall, but this was quickly amended.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The Romans initially planned to build forts every 10 kilometres (6 miles), but this was soon revised to every 3.3 kilometres (2 miles), resulting in a total of nineteen forts along the wall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The best preserved but also one of the smallest forts is Rough Castle Fort.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] In addition to the forts, there are at least nine smaller fortlets, very likely on Roman mile spacings, which formed part of the original scheme, some of which were later replaced by forts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] The most visible fortlet is Kinneil, at the eastern end of the Wall, near Bo'ness.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] There was once a remarkable Roman structure within sight of the Antonine Wall at Stenhousemuir, which took its name from the Roman "stone house".
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] This was Arthur's O'on, a circular stone domed monument or rotunda, which might have been a temple, or a *tropaeum*, a victory monument.
[src:architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/antonine-wall] It was demolished for its stone in 1743, though a replica exists at Penicuik House.
